ggplot2, exercise

Matthias Templ
R Summer School, Vorau 2017

Example 1:

In the following examples, some ggplot2 functions are to be tested and some parameters to be adjusted. Use the data set Cars93. 

data(Cars93, package = "MASS")

More detailed information on the data you obtained with the open the help (?Cars93).

  • Create a scatter plot of the variable MPG.city dependend of Weight.
  • Color the points in blue.
  • Color the points according to variable Origin.

Solution 1: 

require("ggplot2")  
g <- ggplot(Cars93, aes(x=MPG.city, y=Weight))
g <- g + geom_point(color="blue"); g

Solution 1: 

g + geom_point(aes(color=Origin))

Example 2:

  • Create a boxplot of MPG.city.
  • Add points with colouring according to Origin.
  • Make a scatter plot of variable Weight dependend on Horsepower.
  • Add a regression line.
  • Apply it for all groups of variable Origin

Solution 2: 

g <- ggplot(Cars93,aes(x=Type,y=MPG.city))
g <- g + geom_boxplot()
g + geom_point(aes(color=Origin))

Solution 2: 

g <- ggplot(Cars93,aes(x=Weight,y=Horsepower))
g <- g + geom_point()
g + geom_smooth()

Solution 2: 

g <- g + geom_smooth(method="lm") 
g

Solution 2: 

g <- g + facet_wrap(~ Origin) 
g

Example 3: Fine tuning

For the last graphic,

  • take the black/white theme
  • took the symbol size according to the Max.Price and introduce alpha transparency.
  • increase all font sizes.
  • take the font “Times” (New Roman) for annotation
  • For tax reasons, assume that horsepower smaller than 90 are important. Add a (red) line at horsepower 90 and add a grid line as well as make an axis notation for 90.

Solution 3:

Increase font sizes

g <- g + theme_bw()
g

Solution 3:

Increase font sizes

g <- g + geom_point(aes(size = Max.Price), alpha =0.4)
g

Solution 3:

Increase font sizes

g <- g + theme(text = element_text(size=20))
g

Solution 3:

Font Times New Roman

g <- g + theme(text = element_text(family="Times"))
g

Solution 3:

Add (red) line

g <- g + geom_hline(yintercept = 90, colour="red")
g

Solution 3:

New axis notation

g <- g + scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(50, 90, 150, 200, 300))
g

Example 4: tidy data?

produce this graphics:

Example 4: tidy data?

produce this graphics:

library(tidyr)
## ggplot2 needs tidy data!
## use e.g. reshape2::melt or
## tidy::gather
data_long <- gather(olddata_wide, condition, measurement, control:cond2, factor_key=TRUE)
ggplot(data_long, aes(x = time, y = measurement, group=condition, color=condition)) + geom_line()
